<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="111" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
This taxon is broadly Sino-Himalayan-Taiwan-Japanese endemic, distributed within this large area quite disjunctively (although this may reflect the data deficiency). It was described from Sikkim (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8312.1860.tb01045.x" author="Mitten, W" journalOrPublisher="Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" pagination="89 - 128" refId="B49" refString="Mitten, W, 1860. Hepaticae Indiae Orientalis. Journal of the Proceedings of the Linnean Society. Botany 5 (18): 89 - 128, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8312.1860.tb01045.x" title="Hepaticae Indiae Orientalis. Journal of the Proceedings of the Linnean Society." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8312.1860.tb01045.x" volume="5" year="1860">Mitten 1860</bibRefCitation>
), later recorded from Taiwan (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.5735/085.048.0501" author="Wang, J" journalOrPublisher="Annales Botanici Fennici" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" pagination="369 - 395" refId="B74" refString="Wang, J, Lai, MJ, Zhu, RL, 2011. Liverworts and hornworts of Taiwan: An updated checklist and floristic account. Annales Botanici Fennici 48 (5): 369 - 395, DOI: https://doi.org/10.5735/085.048.0501" title="Liverworts and hornworts of Taiwan: An updated checklist and floristic account." url="https://doi.org/10.5735/085.048.0501" volume="48" year="2011">Wang et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
) and eastward from southernmost Japan (
<bibRefCitation author="Inoue, H" journalOrPublisher="Shokubutsu Kenkyu Zasshi" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" pagination="300 - 303" refId="B34" refString="Inoue, H, 1969. Miscellaneous notes on hepatics of Japan (6). Shokubutsu Kenkyu Zasshi 44 (10): 300 - 303" title="Miscellaneous notes on hepatics of Japan (6)." volume="44" year="1969">Inoue 1969</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Yamada, K" journalOrPublisher="The Journal of the Hattori Botanical Laboratory" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" pagination="1 - 106" refId="B77" refString="Yamada, K, Iwatsuki, Z, 2006. Catalog of the hepatics of Japan. The Journal of the Hattori Botanical Laboratory 99: 1 - 106" title="Catalog of the hepatics of Japan." volume="99" year="2006">Yamada and Iwatsuki 2006</bibRefCitation>
). A questionable record is from Hawaii under the name 
<taxonomicName class="Jungermanniopsida" family="Calypogeiaceae" genus="Calypogeia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Calypogeia waialealeensis" order="Jungermanniales" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" phylum="Marchantiophyta" rank="species" species="waialealeensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Calypogeia waialealeensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(H.A. Mill. &amp; Kuwah.) H.A. Mill. (
<bibRefCitation author="Miller, HA" journalOrPublisher="The Journal of the Hattori Botanical Laboratory" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" pagination="271 - 276" refId="B47" refString="Miller, HA, 1967. Oddments of Hawaiian bryology. The Journal of the Hattori Botanical Laboratory 30: 271 - 276" title="Oddments of Hawaiian bryology." volume="30" year="1967">Miller 1967</bibRefCitation>
) - the name synonymized with 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. aeruginosa" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="aeruginosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">C. aeruginosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Inoue, H" journalOrPublisher="Shokubutsu Kenkyu Zasshi" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" pagination="300 - 303" refId="B34" refString="Inoue, H, 1969. Miscellaneous notes on hepatics of Japan (6). Shokubutsu Kenkyu Zasshi 44 (10): 300 - 303" title="Miscellaneous notes on hepatics of Japan (6)." volume="44" year="1969">Inoue (1969)</bibRefCitation>
. From the geographic point of view, this synonymization should be doubted and the status of the populations from Hawaii should be rechecked, including molecular-genetic methods implementing. We recently found 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. aeruginosa" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="aeruginosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">C. aeruginosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in northern Vietnam (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0204561" author="Buczkowska, K" journalOrPublisher="Polish Botanical Journal" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" refId="B15" refString="Buczkowska, K, Bakalin, V, Baczkiewicz, A, Aguero, B, Gonera, P, Ślipiko, M, Szczecinska, M, Sawicki, J, 2018. Does Calypogeiaazurea (Calypogeiaceae, Marchantiophyta) occur outside Europe? Molecular and morphological evidence. PLoS One 13(10): e0204561. https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0204561" title="Does Calypogeiaazurea (Calypogeiaceae, Marchantiophyta) occur outside Europe? Molecular and morphological evidence. PLoS One 13 (10): e 0204561." url="https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0204561" year="2018">Buczkowska et al. 2018</bibRefCitation>
) which may imply its broader distribution in the Meta-Himalaya. The taxon is very distinctive among congeners due to transversely elliptic underleaves as large as or larger than leaves and may be rather mistaken at the time of collection for 
<taxonomicName authority="A.W.Evans, 1907" authorityName="A.W.Evans" authorityYear="1907" class="Jungermanniopsida" family="Lejeuneaceae" genus="Leucolejeunea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Leucolejeunea" order="Porellales" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" phylum="Marchantiophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Leucolejeunea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
due to size, color, leaf orientation and large underleaves (obscuring the fact that the lejeuneaceous lobule is absent here).
</paragraph>
